Question: How do you believe ACME should better support organizations and cultural leaders?

Response ID: resp_659
Response Text: Less rapid and unpredictable change of funding programs, better communication and transparency, listening to more of the creative community and trusting the experienced staff in CAD (the department that has the most extensive funding knowledge and experience of all the departments). 

Sustainable and reliable funding for physical long term spaces that are hubs/incubators/accessible platforms, a needed resource outside of the city run facilities. 

At large we need a better local arts advocacy organization as ACA speaks on behalf of people it doesn't represent, and because they have the time to do so and do so loudly (with a handful of high city leadership connections), then their opinions and insight are held at a high regard, even though in reality its just one very loud man speaking for (and not with) a bunch of people who didn't ask and don't agree all while leveraging data that is incorrect and misrepresentative. In the most generous of evaluations - they have a highly questionable community practice. ACA is just kinda bad at (and doesn't really pursue) what it was actually setup to do. ACME should be able to discern and understand this by listening to community. It fosters distrust and a side eye every time anyone new in staff or leadership at the city gets the wool pulled over their eyes by a dog and pony show that those who have been at it for a while have all grown tired of.

We also need the city of austin to use its reputation and leverage to make cohesive asks to private industry to support cultural programming. A different source of funding outside of HOT tax would be extremely meaningful, and there are many capable orgs who know how to pitch when given the platform in the right rooms. The city could leverage its connections and influence to help create these rooms. Also, theres a bunch of stuff only cities can do that private funders cannot, do these things! 

The two gaps in austin are the pairing of lack of cohesive and trusted advocacy org for the cultural ecosystem and the private funding/philanthropy gap. The city won't be able to solve this but it can be more aware and play better with others to help address it.

